Devotees of free trade.
From Cambridge — — I recently was invited to fill in as a guest speaker in a globalization course taught by two colleagues of mine from Harvard.  "I must warn you."
One of them warned me in advance, saying, "These students are all ardent supporters of globalization."
He once asked students in his first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, resulting in over 90% in favor of the former.
And it's still before the magical effect of comparative advantage begins to be taught.
We know that asking the same questions to representative samples – not Harvard students – in an honest investigation will yield a starkly different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of restricting trade is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students won't come as a surprise.
Because those with higher technological and better educational backgrounds tend to be more inclined to support free trade.
Perhaps they have already expected their own future paths, and made decisions based on that.
Perhaps, they really do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met them, I deliberately put it in another form to ask the same question, and emphasized the distribution effects that trade may have.
The consensus on fair trade has disappeared completely, and even more quickly than I had anticipated.
As soon as the curtain opened, I first asked everyone if they agreed with me to conduct an especially magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas' account disappear—poof!—and at the same time add $300 to John's account, and with social engineering, we can collectively add $100 in value to the class as a whole.
So will they let me play this little trick?
Most of them were opposed to the change, many were hesitant, and only a small fraction were firmly in agreement.
I'm ready to assist.
It's clear that students can hardly tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even if the economic cake has been expanded.
I then asked, why the majority of them would almost instinctively support free trade, which in fact would also lead to a similar – indeed even a more dramatic – reallocation of wealth from losers to winners.
The students all looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume both Nicholas and John own competing small companies.
John worked harder, invested more, and produced better products, so he not only earned $300 more than Nicholas, but also pushed Nicholas's company out of the market and caused it to lose $200.
How many students still support this change?
This time, almost all of them voted in favor — — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John has squeezed Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or is it outsourcing business processes to China, where labor benefits are not yet well-developed?
Or are they employing child labor in Indonesia?
This approval rating for the change is successively reduced as the above options are chosen.
In addition, technological innovation may also lead to certain groups being in a weaker position, just like trade. What's your attitude towards this?
Only a few students are willing to limit the development of technology.
To almost everyone, the idea of banning the production of light bulbs in order to save candle makers' jobs is simply absurd.
Therefore, students are not necessarily opposed to redistribution, but rather opposed to certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most people to us, they are also concerned about the program's fairness.
In order to make a judgment about the outcome of redistribution, we must know the objective environment that produces such a result.
We won't be resentful of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their rivals have been struggling, likely because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic rules, facing very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett were not wealthy due to their own intelligence and hard work, but through cheating, labor law violations, environmental destruction, or foreign government subsidies, our thoughts would be vastly different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved through violating universally accepted domestic moral standards, why should we be satisfied just because it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the redistributive effect to be realized over the long term and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to be indifferent to the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring some negative consequences to certain people in the short term, we are still willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, as trade continues to hit the same group of people – low-skilled blue-collar workers – we will be worried about globalization.
But many economists have chosen to ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute the discomfort with globalization to the stupid and selfish motives of protectionism or ignorance, without realizing that the most critical issue is actually an ethical one.
Because economists are often unable to grasp that international trade can sometimes — certainly not always — lead to some outcomes of income redistribution that we are not willing to accept at home, they are also unable to intervene appropriately in public discussion.
Since they cannot stand on their moral ground, how can they vigorously defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimacy of redistribution effects, we should not thoughtlessly resort to trade restrictions as a response.
There are many pros and cons to weigh, including the possibility that globalization may deprive people in other places of wealth more severely than victims in the United States itself.
But a more fitting discussion should be held in democratic countries, and more conscious and well-considered decisions should be made.
But the practice that only loves globalization because it has made the cake bigger, will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization in the long run.
